│ 💭 Thought 3/15 │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ The critical flaw: When cookies are deleted while already on a dashboard page, the NEXT page navigation triggers middleware that sets locals.isAuthenticated = false. If dashboard pages check auth in their frontmatter and try to redirect, this happens AFTER the page component has started to load. Astro's page lifecycle: middleware -> page frontmatter -> component render. If frontmatter tries to redirect after rendering starts, ResponseSentError occurs. The middleware needs to handle protected routes BEFORE calling next().   │

│ 💭 Thought 4/18 │
├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Hypothesis: The middleware should intercept protected routes (like /dashboard/*) and redirect to login BEFORE calling next() if authentication fails. However, this doesn't solve the core problem - we need to handle the case where a user is ALREADY on a protected page when their session expires. A client-side solution is needed for already-rendered pages. The architecture needs two layers: 1) Middleware-level protection for new navigations, 2) Client-side session monitoring for already-loaded pages.   │

│ 💭 Thought 6/20 │
├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ FOUND THE BUG! DashLayout.astro lines 26-28 attempt to redirect if not authenticated. The sequence is: middleware runs -> sets locals.isAuthenticated=false -> calls next() -> DashLayout loads -> tries to redirect. But if any component rendering has started or response headers sent, the redirect fails with ResponseSentError. The architecture flaw: auth redirects must happen in middleware BEFORE next(), not in layouts/pages AFTER next().   │
└───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

│ Actually, looking at DashLayout lines 33-35, it sets headers BEFORE the redirect check. `Astro.response.headers.set()` might commit the response, making subsequent redirects impossible. The flow is: frontmatter executes top-to-bottom -> headers set (lines 33-35) -> auth check (line 26) -> try to redirect BUT response already committed from header operations. This is the bug! Headers should only be set AFTER auth check passes.   │

│ Key finding: CookieGuard exists but CookieModal.vue doesn't exist (grep found no files). This is an incomplete implementation. The real issue is becoming clearer: when cookies are deleted while on a dashboard page, the NEXT client-side navigation (via View Transitions) triggers middleware that sets isAuthenticated=false, then DashLayout tries to redirect, but the View Transition has already started the response stream. We need a TWO-LAYER defense: 1) Fix middleware to handle protected routes BEFORE next(), 2) Add client-side session monitoring to detect cookie deletion and show modal instead of crashing.   │

│ Solution architecture emerging: Layer 1 (Middleware Protection) - Check path against protected routes list (/dashboard/*), if protected and not authenticated, redirect BEFORE next(). This prevents DashLayout from ever running unauthenticated. Layer 2 (Client-Side Monitoring) - A SessionMonitor component that periodically checks if session cookie exists, detects deletion/expiration, shows modal "Session expired, please log out and log back in" with logout button. This handles the edge case where user is ALREADY on a rendered page when session expires.   │

│ Edge cases to handle: 1) User opens multiple tabs - SessionMonitor should coordinate via localStorage event to show modal in all tabs simultaneously, 2) Rapid navigation during session expiry - middleware redirect prevents any page load, 3) API calls failing with 401 - existing error handlers should also trigger session expired modal, 4) Race condition: cookie deleted between middleware check and page render - SessionMonitor catches this, 5) Modal dismissed accidentally - should be non-dismissible (no close button, backdrop click disabled), only logout button works.   │

│ Additional resilience layer: Global error boundary. Wrap entire app in error boundary that catches ResponseSentError and other Astro rendering errors, displays fallback UI with "Something went wrong" message and logout button. This is the ultimate failsafe if both middleware and SessionMonitor fail. However, error boundaries in Astro are tricky - we might need a Vue error boundary component that wraps the main slot in DashLayout, using onErrorCaptured hook.   │

│ Performance consideration: SessionMonitor polling every 30 seconds could be expensive. Optimize by: 1) Only run on dashboard pages (already scoped via DashLayout), 2) Use requestIdleCallback for non-critical polling, 3) Debounce API calls - if cookie missing, immediately show modal and stop polling, 4) Consider using Broadcast Channel API instead of localStorage events for better multi-tab communication (more modern, lower overhead), 5) Cleanup: clear interval on component unmount to prevent memory leaks.   │

│ API interceptor enhancement: Check if there's a global API client that could intercept 401 responses. If API calls return 401 (unauthorized), automatically trigger the session expired modal. This creates a third layer of defense: 1) Middleware catches expired sessions on navigation, 2) SessionMonitor catches cookie deletion on static pages, 3) API interceptor catches 401 responses from background API calls. All three converge to the same UX: show modal with "Session expired, please log out".   │

│ UX considerations for modal: 1) Should be visually distinct from regular modals - use warning/error styling (amber/red colors), 2) Icon: Heroicons "exclamation-triangle" or similar, 3) Copy should be clear and actionable: "Your session has expired" (title), "For security, please log out and sign back in to continue." (description), 4) Single primary action button: "Log Out" (not "Okay" or "Close"), 5) No backdrop click or ESC key dismissal - force user to acknowledge by clicking logout, 6) Consider adding a "Why did this happen?" expandable section explaining common causes (browser privacy settings, manual cookie deletion, long inactivity).   │

│ 💭 Thought 24/28 │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Security consideration: The middleware token validation (userApi.currentUser()) makes an API call on EVERY request when there's a cached session. This could be expensive and slow. Optimization: Add a timestamp to cached session, only validate if last validation was > 5 minutes ago. Store validation timestamp in session: session.set("lastValidated", Date.now()). On each request, check if (Date.now() - lastValidated) > 5 * 60 * 1000, only then call userApi.currentUser(). This reduces API calls while still catching expired tokens within 5-minute window. SessionMonitor fills the gap for detection between validations.   │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

│ State management for session monitoring: Create a sessionStore using nanostore atom to track session expiry state globally. This allows: 1) Multiple components to react to session expiry (SessionMonitor, API interceptors, etc.), 2) Prevent duplicate modals - check if already shown before displaying, 3) Coordinate multi-tab communication via localStorage sync. Store structure: `{ isExpired: boolean, lastChecked: number, modalShown: boolean }`. SessionMonitor updates this store, SessionExpiredModal reads from it. Use persistentAtom to survive page refreshes temporarily.   │

│ 💭 Thought 26/28 │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Error boundary strategy: Since Astro doesn't have built-in error boundaries like React, we need a different approach. Instead of trying to catch ResponseSentError (which is too late), prevent it entirely through the layered defense. If ResponseSentError still occurs, it will show Astro's default error page - this is acceptable as last resort since our three layers (middleware redirect, SessionMonitor, API interceptor) should prevent 99.9% of cases. However, we could add a custom Astro error page (src/pages/500.astro) with a logout button as final fallback.   │

│ 💭 Thought 28/28 │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Final architecture summary: Three-layer resilient authentication system. Layer 1 (Middleware): Intercepts protected routes (/dashboard/*), redirects to /login if !isAuthenticated BEFORE next() - prevents ResponseSentError by handling auth before page rendering. Layer 2 (Client-Side Monitor): SessionMonitor component polls cookie every 30s, shows SessionExpiredModal on deletion - handles edge case where user is on static page when session expires. Layer 3 (API Interceptor): Global error handler catches 401 responses, triggers same modal - handles background API failures. All layers converge to same UX: non-dismissible modal with "Session expired, please log out". This creates comprehensive coverage with no crash scenarios. Implementation is incremental, testable, and performant.   │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
